@totalactor467 As a rule of thumb, it tends to not work. But I think that's because it's usually done as a shortcut to get audiences to support a new character. 

Another example of them doing this was Thor and Captain Marvel in Endgame. There's that awful moment when Thor looks at her and says "I like this one." That's done with a wink to the audience. It's saying "You like Thor. Well, Thor likes Captain Marvel. So you'd better like her too. Because he didn't bother giving her a personality."

The few examples where passing on the legacy works is when writers have a full character underneath the uniform and code name they take on. Cases in the comics like some of the "replacement" Robins.

